So we worked really hard on getting enough social pressure on the elections board to call the Dept of Justice. They did, and then the DOJ turned out to be one guy, "Chip" who gave legal counsel in a secret executive session and did not put anything on paper to hold him to. As it turns out, the other guys have some serious political connections through the college democrats, I'm talking Kennedy connections. I think Patrick will be governor some day. Anyway, it is highly likely that Chip has his own agenda. So, the election is pretty much over, Rudy lost.&nbsp;

Next years elections begin today. Later tonight I should begin working on my website that chroncles all this and unites the student group that will lobby Stodent Government because believe me on this we need one. Nobody knows the resources $12million! that are available except special interests. The&nbsp;ASPSU themselves are always traveling to Salem to meet important people but in the meantime intruders like the "Center for Bio-Ethical Reform" and Sizemore's mercenaries invade the heart of our campus.&nbsp;

So the first issue for the lobby group is defunding "Students for Life" the group that brought those protestors here.
I am going to create social capitol on campus by fighting little fights like this. By next years election I will have created a party that is focused on the myriad issues that affect students here on campus. And we will win.

Once we win we will use the resources to activate the student body. For example, the&nbsp;current government goes to Salem to "lobby" as if they are changing votes in Salem that always come down to party lines anyway. Once they even organized a "rally" where they e-mailed students to get on a bus and travel to Salem to "rally" on the front steps.&nbsp;The students who whent said it was cool. I ask them "who is your represntative?", and they do not know. We can get so much more accomplished by organizing letter writing campaigns. This way student government actually interacts with people and teaches them about government. It builds social connections. ASPSU sees themselves as a lobby organization. This is politics that places them on a higher level than the rest of the students by empowring themselves instead of the people. This is politics taught by special interests like OSPIRG and the scariest thing is that these people will even tell you that. They do not see the big picture and realize how weak it is. ASPSU is practicing the politics of co-option. The political elites let them in to their "process" and act like they care. We are going to practice the politics of confrontation here at PSU after I am running the show. Then you are really going to see some shit.

1. Social Capital is the bonds of trust and unity people build by communicating and working together. Social Capital is a tool that helps groups to accomplish social and political goals that could have not been reached by individuals working seperately. Social Capitol is, to me, the ability of the people to challenge the power of government. Bonding social capitol is the type&nbsp;that &nbsp;similiar people within the same group aquire e.g. the Italian-American society. Bridging capitol is the type that happens when different groups work together, e.g. Christians and hippies at a peace rally.

2. In order for social capital to develop through working together and communication, the people need some sort of work to do. City Repair provides people with the opportunity to do that work. Benches are nice, and they do provide a public place, but building the bench together is what creates the social capital. It would be meaningless for cit repair to buy a bench and install it, although it may require less upkeep and seem more efficiant.&nbsp;

3. Question 3 to be answered later...

4. Unfortunately, my personel experiences involving community is rather tragic. My family has been obliterated by various social and personal problems. I spent a good portion of my young adulthood as an "undesirable". And nobody can understand just what I am so pissed about, which just seems to make me feel more isolated. I am lucky enough to attend college for two reasons- One, I found reasonable paying job, and two, financial aid. However, the &nbsp;job involved tons of hard labor, and now I walk with a limp and live in pain. I used to be an athlete for Christ's sakes, and now I can't even run. Nobody at that job I was at for seven years cares about me today.&nbsp;
So Honestly, when it comes to bridging social capital I can not name one activity I am a part of that I would identify as bridging. However, I have made myself part of some forms of bonding capital. I have become active in student government, and by the time all is said and done I'll have more friends than enemies. Also. we are part of the community garden. This has been really cool because once you work together with someone, you are friends. I can't explain, it just happens. We meet other people like us at random times who are just digging in the garden.

Assignment 3

1. I think the most successful gathering place in P.S.U. is the Food for Thought Cafe. It is a really comfortable place to do work and talk at the same time. Comfortable furniture and computer access. Food, obviously, but there is a certain dimension to the place that is special- the service is incredibly slow and inefficiant. Thus, only people who are chilling ever go there. It is quite funny to watch people in the line, every fifth one or so becomes incredibly agitated.&nbsp;

The park block area is an interesting case study. It seems to be an almost ideal place as a public gathering- great places to sit, food , people, chess boards (which I use, if you play, Mr. Pedro....), even a stage. While people do meet and talk to each other, especially on nice days, it just seems to me the space is horribly unutilized. I think&nbsp;this is so because the space is gridded out and people see it as just a path to their next class, mostly. The crazy christians make good use of it, that is for sure. And the petitioners, and the PACS, and greenpeace, and OSPIRG, all these freaking outside groups seem to tell people "Move along, lest someone bother you for their personal gain."&nbsp;

2. Recently, I "canvassed" at the Urban center. I rate it as a very good use of urban space, with some flaws. There are places to sit, water, food, "triangulation". It feels safe from intruders and undesirables. I talked to students there who were very eager to talk with me about school politics. Because it is seperated from the Park Blocks, the people there had not been berated by campaign propaganda and empty promises. However a frakinf Tri-Met train comes through. Sometimes I walk around not really paying attention, allright I am stoned, but still, a man should be able to walk with his dog in safety from a train smacking him in the face.

3. The dialouge dome is cool because food can be cooked in it, although it is going to be harder than I thought to do that. The overhang&nbsp;and bench area provide a nice area for chilling. People have commented on a "secluded" feeling and I agree. I saw a woman reading in there by herself. Once that area is claimed by a person or group, it seems to be their's. However, while campaigning, I approached people there and mostly people in the area were receptive to conversation.

. The book bench is funny. At first I thought it was gaudy and took away from the architectural beauty of the building. But it is a cool place to sit. One can see down on the "action" (hotties..) on the park blocks. It is quite witty that the design is shaped like a book. Unfortunately, the smokers like to hang out there, but even if a bunch of people are smoking there, that is still community.&nbsp;

5. The Pioneer square has just about everything on the list that makes for a good public meeting place and it that. I watched Ferris Bueller's Day off there on&nbsp;a Friday night on a jumbo screen with a thousand other people. They even had free popcorn from a crporate sponsor. I have seen really good musical acts like Shoehorn and March Forth at other corproate sponsored events.

There is definately places to sit, thanks to the layered wall. Other people, I enjoy the hackey sack guys, hell even the "undesirables" are funny to watch. The philly steak&nbsp; sub cart is the shizzle. sometimes I play chess there. I just wish security there did not seem so mean and intrusive..."Move along, they seem to say, you need&nbsp;to be protected through this dangerous area." One time, I was deeply involved in a chess game. Security guy came up and said "How is the chess, fellas?" In an overly frienly voice. Just so you know, chess players can be extremely anti-social. He was not welcome to talk. No one was. It felt like he was showing off his power by interupting us because he hung around waiting for an answer as if this was an interogation. So, of course I said "Is this an interogation?" He actually said "Carry on" as if we needed his permission to use the chess board. prick.
